There are quite a few that work well with the column method:

Potatoes are good for this type of gardening; however, to fully harvest them you often need to pull apart the column, which could make a mess. Potatoes grow well in the tyre (tire), pot, or mounded methods. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1e\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1e\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Tomatoes are excellent for this type of gardening, as are sweetcorn / maize, capsicums / bell peppers, etc. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f2\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f2\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Climbers such as beans, peas and cucumbers. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d5\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d5\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Brassicas such as cabbage, cauliflower, broccoli, etc., lend themselves well to this method but only in low volumes. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/33\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/33\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Annual herbs such as basil, thyme, rosemary, oregano, etc., are great options. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/63\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet5.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/63\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet5.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Melons and other such as pumpkins or squashes can be grown by this method as well. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/5a\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet6.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/5a\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet6.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

There are many more, such as: strawberries, root vegetables such as parsnip, beetroot, turnip and carrot, and other leafy greens such as silverbeet, spinach, etc. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/48\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet7.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/48\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet7.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

text:
 Do some research first. Consider where you intend to place the column, as well as the type of produce you intend to grow. Most importantly, consider how big you would like the column to be and an estimate of the circumference of the column. This is best done by drawing a simple plan of where the stakes will fit in, with an estimate of the distance between each stake and then measuring the distance around the outside edge of all the stakes, plus a few inches (centimeters) spare to secure it. This way you can estimate how much wire you will need. Ideally the column should have full sun, or if you are in a hot environment, dappled shade. It should be sitting on soil, rather than on concrete or paving stones, as the soil will stain the pavement. If you are in an area that freezes, you might not get a winter use out of this method if you have deep frosts as the column has a higher surface area above ground exposed to air and therefore is more likely to freeze. Consider the types of vegetables you wish to grow. There are quite a few that work well with the column method:

Potatoes are good for this type of gardening; however, to fully harvest them you often need to pull apart the column, which could make a mess. Potatoes grow well in the tyre (tire), pot, or mounded methods. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1e\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1e\/Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-Vegetables-in-Wire-Columns-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


